Especially when there is so much I want to do, while I'm still somewhat young enough to enjoy it. Write a book, build a hotrod, learn to weld, design a video game, make a pen and paper rpg. I want to share it with the world, but I have no hope that the world will see it.

Now I'm older, I own a house, I'm married, I work in excavation and it pays the bills. My creative time has limits. I'm left dreading a thought, that I'm spending my youth and creative energy in the wrong place. When I've fail so much, I worry that I will just be let down again.

I create to live, its who I am. And when I was young I was filled with hope and wonder at this online world that rewards us creative types, but now that I've seen past the curtain, seen how the sausage is made, lived the life of the professional content creator, I long for hope.
I made it pretty far, but every inch of ground I gained I've had to claw at and desperately hold onto at great cost to myself, while others skip past me seemingly effortlessly.

There is a literal "x-factor" that makes someones efforts in this industry either succeed, or fail. It cant be taught, replicated, or faked.  It either is, or is not.  People like me, without "it" can try, and we can get somewhere. But its like ice skating uphill.

This may come as a shock, but something I've come to accept over the past few years is that despite my best efforts, talent, and expertise in online video production and social media; there is SOMETHING that some people have that makes them succeed, and I do not have IT.

I do my morning routine, get ready for the day. Then I sit down on the couch and scroll through various social media, looking for my morning entertainment, interactions, some sign that my dreams are still in tact, some feeling of hope. What I stare at instead is my home screen

@Trauma1337 Restricted mode is this "harmless thing" if you listen to what youtube tells you about it, but the reality is that its a broad category your whole channel is put in that you can never get back out of, and there is no way to truly measure what is happening.

@Trauma1337 and this is merely the visible effect that restricted mode has, what you're not seeing is how it changes how ads are served, how your channel gets displayed as a suggested video, and how that video ranks in search engines.  Which I can tell you, it affects it greatly.

@Trauma1337 on top of that, if you are a user who connects through a school network, that network most likely will switch your account to use restricted mode, switching back to unrestricted is something you will manually have to do.

@Trauma1337 I'm more concerned about the effect it has on SEO.  This also only applies to adults over 18, people who are using their own wifi network, and people who live in countries that dont restrict content.
